{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8742d6f2-c3dc-439d-8c27-bc8e9ebcd0cd","content":"The standard approach in .NET is to **wrap file system calls behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n```\n\nThen create a real implementation for production and a fake/mock for tests:\n\n```csharp\npublic class PhysicalFileSystem : IFileSystem\n{\n    public string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);\n    public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => File.WriteAllText(path, contents);\n    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => Directory.Exists(path);\n}\n```\n\n**Alternatives:**\n\n1. **`System.IO.Abstractions`** — a popular NuGet package that provides `IFileSystem` out of the box with a `MockFileSystem` for tests. Saves you from writing your own.\n\n2. **`Microsoft.Extensions.FileProviders`** — useful if you only need read access.\n\n**Key points:**\n- Inject `IFileSystem` via constructor DI.\n- In tests, use a mock (Moq, NSubstitute) or an in-memory fake.\n- Keep the interface narrow — only expose what you actually use (Interface Segregation Principle).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c843333b-0c63-4e40-9fbf-bb656ae9a86a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to make file system operations (`File.WriteAllText`, `File.ReadAllText`, `Directory.Exists`) testable in their .NET project. This is a common software design question about abstracting file system dependencies for unit testing.\n\nThis is a general software engineering question - I don't need to look at any files or run any commands. I can answer directly with best practices.","outputTokens":423,"requestId":"E3EB:FA207:21EAF0F:2591375:6A0535C3"},"id":"f1771fc4-730e-463d-9c9e-6ddbafb7dece","timestamp":"2026-05-14T02:39:09.831Z","parentId":"27c27521-930d-4d6b-a815-cef32f49399f"}
